<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-reciprocals-using-division" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Reciprocals using Division</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_4szotn8g">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_im9k8igm">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_6blsa8eo">
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_utvy8ypk">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_pc9h4gpv">
                        1.1 Real Numbers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lrrytmvu">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p xml:id="auto_nbxmh1l2">
                        Finding reciprocals of real numbers using division.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_j84x04fy" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_f5qpt5jx">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ikle6zzp" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8if67ffh">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_fare9hmi" component="lesson-plan">

                <p xml:id="auto_gpcmtx7n"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_kvwwpzes">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bqngl3xq">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that the reciprocal of a number x is <m>1/x</m>, and when multiplied by the original number, the product is 1. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5apxezjo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qzlzkt2r">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Find reciprocals of real numbers using division <m>(1 ÷ x)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ozazpkdi">
                        <p xml:id="auto_9feqzasp">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply reciprocals to solve real-world problems involving rates, distances, and time.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        </objectives>

        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

 <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_dj25kcjs">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_pi6gydvn">
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_irmtui3s">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_8easfqjz">
                    To activate prior knowledge about fractions and division through a collaborative, hands-on task.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_zmg2qzsk">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ab8l0bso">
                    The teacher circulates among the groups, listening to their discussions and observing their methods for finding reciprocals. The teacher asks probing questions to guide discovery (e.g., "What happens when you multiply a number by its reciprocal?", "How can you check if your answer is correct?", "What do you notice about the reciprocal of a fraction?"). The teacher will then select a few groups to share their findings.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_5b4112ai">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_01s5g5iq">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_tze5by97">
                <term>Materials:</term> Paper, a ruler, and scissors.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_o925h3hj">
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_u93igbl4">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_zs4i5nlm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vjq0of4v">
                            We're going to cut out different rectangles that have the same area.
                            <ol marker="1.">
                                <li xml:id="auto_yxjn9ku0">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_s6b7dgv2">
                                        Cut out a square of length 1cm. (If your ruler has inches on it, it might be easier to cut out a square of length 1 inch.) 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_s0ofvddn">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_sey3wtte">
                                        Cut out a rectangle with length 2cm and height 0.5cm.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_1wfwz7cl">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_e6u2a1i9">
                                        Cut out a rectangle with length 3cm and height 0.33cm.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_vo9feifp">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_wkqslhzj">
                                        Cut out a rectangle with height 0.5cm and length 2cm.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_hbmpan3c">
                        <p xml:id="auto_xb5m0vg0">
                            Arrange your rectangles so that their bottom left corners are on top of each other, and their lengths are parralel, like the black boxes in <xref ref="fig-reciprocal-interactive"/>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ba7gxvnk">
                        <p xml:id="auto_1wdy09lx">
                            Visually confirm that all your rectangles have roughly the same area as the square (which is <m>1 \text{ cm}^2</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_kny5gggl" component="html">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ujyf84ue">
                            Consider the following interactive:
                        </p>
                        <figure xml:id="fig-reciprocal-interactive">
                            <title>Reciprocals</title>        
                            <caption>Using <m>y = \frac{1}{x}</m> to find reciprocals</caption>
                            <interactive xml:id="interactive-reciprocals" platform="jsxgraph" width="80%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/reciprocal.js">
                                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-reciprocal-grid" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
                            </interactive>
                        </figure>
                        <p xml:id="auto_1dw42744">
                            As you drag the point <m>P</m>, the red rectangle has length <m>x</m> and height <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>. Given that the area remains constant at <m>1 \text{ cm}^2</m>, and (as we will cover in <xref ref="sec-area-of-polygons"/>), area is length <m>\times</m> height, what do you know about <m>x \times \frac{1}{x}</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tg4d9s2m" component="print">
                        <p xml:id="auto_8waokpyy">
                            Examine the following figure:
                        </p>
                        <image source="reciprocal-graph.png">      
                            <caption>Using <m>y = \frac{1}{x}</m> to find reciprocals</caption>                      
                        </image>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3q5rdk0m">
                            The red curve connects all the top right corners of rectangles with area 1, containing length <m>x</m> and height <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>. Given that the area remains constant at <m>1 \text{ cm}^2</m>, and (as we will cover in <xref ref="sec-area-of-polygons"/>), area is length <m>\times</m> height, what do you know about <m>x \times \frac{1}{x}</m>?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="two-point-five">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qazqmnco">
                            If a rectangle has length 2.5cm, but area <m>1 \text{ cm}^2</m> (like the other rectangles), what must its height be? Use the figure to find out.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bnyss7yc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_suzorvqk">
                            Write 2.5 as a fraction, as well as your previous answer. What do you notice about these fractions? Does this generalise to other fractions?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_6xv866i9">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_fuqj268t">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_o0ijysrk">
                    8 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_dwhnheko">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_r23teziv">
                    To formalize the concepts and properties learners discovered in the anchor task.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_r8r9q1nz">
        <p xml:id="auto_xgosrijv">
            The reciprocal of a number is the number that, when multiplied by the original number, gives a product of <m>1</m>.
        </p>    
        <p xml:id="auto_0eu9twl6">
          In other words the reciprocal of a real number <m>x</m> is <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>, except when <m>x=0</m> since division by zero is undefined. 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qtdoc8bf">
            Taking the reciprocal of a fraction swaps the numerator and denominator: <m>1 \div \frac{a}{b} = \frac{1}{\frac{a}{b}} = \frac{b}{a}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_621qm87p">
            For example: 
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_7vbb0hl5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_xxqvh3iw">
                        The reciprocal of <m>2</m> is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7zfbe6nu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_l2gvkfal">
                        The reciprocal of <m>\frac{3}{5}</m>, using division, is  <m>1 \div \frac{3}{5} = \frac{5}{3}</m>. You can find this using long division.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8w45u4nr">
            <alert>To find the reciprocal of a real number, we can use long division</alert>
        </p>

    </insight>

     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_9rplk5zz">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_ynuj0uuf">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_mtpy6oa8">
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_pobpw2qc">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3kcrdigz">
                    To apply the learned concepts and procedures to solve varied problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8q5i3gh0">
                <title>Leaning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_inhrevsg">
                    Learners work on a set of problems individually or in pairs. The problems are designed to move from simple classification to application and reasoning.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_jbfx8tu4">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_kjaow94u">
                    The teacher monitors Learners as they work, providing support where needed and encouraging Learners to explain their reasoning using the formal properties discussed in <xref ref="auto_r8r9q1nz"/>
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_0av4vb1b">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_lpqvdnu4">
                Find the reciprocal of <m>5</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_zlmnekm5"> Using long division:
                <tabular>
                        <row>
                            <cell></cell>
                            <cell bottom="medium"><m>0.2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>10</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>-</m></cell>
                            <cell bottom="medium"><m>10</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell></cell>
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_j1mgu5tp">
                Which is <m>= 0.2</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    
    <example xml:id="auto_uiyilm29">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_hdpko97j">
             Find the reciprocal (to 5 decimal places) of the following numbers using long division.  
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xv0zzhjp">
             <ol xml:id="auto_g3luxmsx">
                <li xml:id="auto_v92b1vdj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nyeltlo8">
                       <m>11</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_947yzcr0">
                    <p xml:id="auto_a31rd5f9">
                        <m>4.2</m> 
                    </p>
                </li>
             </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_3t1157do">
                <ol xml:id="auto_e7782k4a">
                    <li xml:id="auto_cs5wyf9g">
                        <p xml:id="auto_t6ftjrpr">
                          The reciprocal of <m>11</m> is <m>\frac{1}{11}</m>, so we need to do long devision of 1 divided by 11.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_hvtg8yzs">
                            <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image label="fractions111">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \node at (0,0) {$\longdivision[stage=6, repeating decimal style = none]{1.0000}{11}$};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                            </image>    
                        </p>
                       
                        <p xml:id="auto_yrph5bru">
                            Hence, the reciprocal of <m>11</m> using division is <m>1\div 11 = 0.090909\ldots</m>, which is <m>0.09091</m> to five decimal places.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_91opibhn">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qi8ualrn">
                            The reciprocal of <m>4.2</m> according to definition is <m>\frac{1}{4.2}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_xqpfypsu">
                            We can rerwrite <m>\frac{1}{4.2}</m> as <m> \frac{1}{4.2}\times \frac{10}{10} </m>
                            <md>                                                                  
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{10}{42} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{21} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_3oyqf859">
                        Dividing <m>5</m> by <m>21</m> we have:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_vtufx2vw">
                            <image width="50%">
                            <latex-image label="fractions521">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \node at (0,0) {$\longdivision[5, repeating decimal style = none]{5}{21}$};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                            </image>    
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_oil4uo1m">
                           Therefore, the reciprocal of <m>4.2</m> given to 4 decimal places is <m>0.2381</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_ub0ae2i9">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_z0wmt23s">
                If <m>\frac{1}{x} = 0.7</m>, find <m>x - \frac{1}{x}</m> to 3 decimal places.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_vgwbr9a5">
                Given <m>\frac{1}{x} = 0.7</m>, we compute <m>x</m> as the reciprocal of
                <m>0.7</m> using division:
                <m>x = 1 \div 0.7 = 10 \div 7</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gn5rju2c">
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="fractions107">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \node at (0,0) {$\longdivision[4, repeating decimal style = none]{10}{7}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>    
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_dja6nz6p">
                Hence <m>x = 1.4285\ldots</m>, which to three decimal places is <m>1.429</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_rg7xmzcd">
                Now compute the required expression:
                <m>x - \frac{1}{x} = 1.429 - 0.7 = 0.729</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_dbgxe284">
                Therefore <m>x - \frac{1}{x} = 0.729</m> (to three decimal places).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Evaluate </title>
        <p xml:id="auto_dqe52u8t">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_0ce885s0">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_q3e1y6lg">
                    8 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_hx43t5rl">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5534nj1h">
                    To formatively assess individual Learner understanding of the lesson objectives.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_zw0e7rtn">
                <title>Leaning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_k3cic9ye">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_6olyvjpy">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_d97jpeh6">
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge Learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

